  "response": "Trailing zeros in a factorial come from factors of 10 = 2 × 5, and since factors of 2 are far more plentiful than factors of 5, the count of trailing zeros equals the number of times 5 divides into 137!. Legendre's formula gives that count by summing floor divisions by successive powers of 5:\n\n- Multiples of 5 up to 137: ⌊137/5⌋ = 27\n- Multiples of 25 (each contributes an extra 5): ⌊137/25⌋ = 5\n- Multiples of 125 (a third 5): ⌊137/125⌋ = 1\n- Multiples of 625: ⌊137/625⌋ = 0, so we stop.\n\nTotal: 27 + 5 + 1 = 33 factors of 5, and more than enough 2s to pair with each one.\n\nANSWER: 33",
